housing. I am currently staying in a rented house and I pay approximately 9 USD per month. I work in a nonprofit organization as the Monitoring and Evaluation Coordinator. I pay my staff on time and this way my expatriate employees get to stay in Malawi with their families. I always feel that even when I rent I can just have enough food to eat not more than 25 USD every month. The government is currently pushing some housing programs where there is a range of houses for very very extremely low income earners. The myth is that you are now getting a house for free when you manage to raise 50 USD. I have noted that out of the few people in Malawi that I know, 99% will never be able to raise 50 USD. The government does not have any solution whereby they just pay you 25 USD so that you can be able to pay your paying your rent and also be able feed your children. There is a chapel near my house that has a soup kitchen that feeds up to 500 people a night. I do volunteer there as a kitchen manager and I have also noted that most time people have nothing to eat. Therefore the 50 USD to buy a house that your employer should see as “peace of mind” you end up buying food for the whole family.

Thomas Johnson

Lilongwe Malawi

December 31st, 2009 at 9:16 am
